Since you're air-gapped, I'll stick to `curl` + `jq` (both usually preinstalled, no pip/npm needed). JFrog gives you a few different APIs depending on what "details" you want — repo browsing, Docker registry API, or AQL for bulk metadata. Here's the full toolkit:

## 1. List all repositories (to confirm your docker repo name/type)

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/repositories?type=local" | jq '.[] | select(.packageType=="Docker")'
```

## 2. List all images (repositories/folders) inside the docker repo

Using the **Docker Registry API v2** (built into Artifactory):

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/docker/<docker-repo-name>/v2/_catalog?n=1000" | jq
```

> `n=1000` sets page size — if you have more images, use the `Link` header in the response for pagination.

## 3. List all tags for a specific image

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/docker/<docker-repo-name>/v2/<image-name>/tags/list" | jq
```

## 4. Get manifest details (digest, layers, size) for a specific tag

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  -H "Accept: application/vnd.docker.distribution.manifest.v2+json" \
  "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/docker/<docker-repo-name>/v2/<image-name>/manifests/<tag>" | jq
```

For just the digest (via HEAD, faster):

```bash
curl -s -k -I -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  -H "Accept: application/vnd.docker.distribution.manifest.v2+json" \
  "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/docker/<docker-repo-name>/v2/<image-name>/manifests/<tag>"
```

## 5. Bulk metadata dump (best for your use case — all images at once)

This is the most useful one for a full inventory: **AQL (Artifactory Query Language)** pulls path, size, created date, modified date, checksums for everything in one shot:

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  -H "Content-Type: text/plain" \
  -X POST "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/search/aql" \
  -d 'items.find({"repo":"<docker-repo-name>"}).include("name","repo","path","size","created","modified","sha256")' \
  | jq '.results'
```

Filter to only `manifest.json` files to get one row per image:tag (avoids layer blob clutter):

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  -H "Content-Type: text/plain" \
  -X POST "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/search/aql" \
  -d 'items.find({"repo":"<docker-repo-name>","name":"manifest.json"}).include("name","repo","path","size","created","modified")' \
  | jq -r '.results[] | [.path, .size, .created] | @tsv'
```

## 6. Storage summary (repo size, image count) — quick sanity check

```bash
curl -s -k -u "$JFROG_USER:$JFROG_API_KEY" \
  "https://<jfrog-host>/artifactory/api/storage/<docker-repo-name>?list&deep=1&listFolders=1" | jq
```

### Notes for your setup
- Use `-k` since `gitlab.sbi`/JFrog likely runs self-signed certs internally (consistent with your other tooling).
- Prefer `$JFROG_API_KEY` (or an Artifactory **access token**) over a personal password — check if your bastion already has one exported as an env var.
- The AQL query (#5) is the one I'd actually script — you can pipe the `manifest.json` output into a CSV/report loop matching your `apply_repo_governance.py` / `log()` house style (stdout + dated file under `D:\Mr Om\Python_script\`).

